............................................................................................................................................................................................................... 81 http://beafreelanceblogger.com/ BeAFreelanceBlogger.com Page 3 Back to Contents Page Here’s Your Ultimate List of Better-Paying Blogs The one thing you desperately need as a freelance blogger is a client who pays a fair rate. 
Without at least one client, you’re not even in business. 
Before I found my ideal clients, I often wished I had an easy list of places that pay writers a decent amount for a blog post. 
So that’s what I’m giving you. 
Here’s my list of 75 blogs that pay $50 US (roughly £30 in the UK) or more per post. 
Some of them accept simpler posts at a lower rate, but why would you choose less if you can earn more? 
Where do you get this information? 
Some of it I found by searching the internet for simple keyword combinations (like “paid” along with “write for us” or “guest blogging”). 
Sometimes blog owners and editors contact me and ask to be listed. 
Some of these blogs I’ve written for, and some I was told about by other bloggers. 
Many thanks to Lisa C. Baker, who contributed info on health, parenting and family blogs. 
And HUGE thanks to Lauren Tharp of LittleZotz Writing, who researched pay structures and chased editors for me. 
(Lauren is also Be a Freelance Blogger’s Community Manager and Guest Post Editor, so you’ll see her on the blog a lot.) http://beafreelanceblogger.com/ http://littlezotz.com/ BeAFreelanceBlogger.com Page 4 Back to Contents Page Can I really write for them? 
Many of these blogs welcome submissions from writers and non-writers, and some will even help you to refine your blog post after you submit it. 
So don’t be put off if you’re “not a professional”, “not a blogger” or “not a writer” yet! 
Contact your favourites and let them know what you can contribute that will interest their visitors. 
For more advice about making contact, pitching your ideas and impressing your editors, check out these blog posts: ● The Perfect Pitch Email to Get Your Guest Post Accepted ● Here’s What Real Blog Editors Look For in Your Pitches ● 7 Winning Ways to End Your Pitch, Query or LOI ● Why Your Guest Posts Keep Getting Rejected ● Why Freelance Blogging is NOT a Numbers Game ● The Jedi’s Guide to Conquering Your Freelance Blogging Fears ● How to Develop Your Relationship With an Editor ● 5 Ways to Rock Your Guest Post After They Approve Your Pitch http://beafreelanceblogger.com/ http://beafreelanceblogger.com/perfect-blog-pitch/ http://beafreelanceblogger.com/how-to-pitch-blog-editors/ http://beafreelanceblogger.com/how-to-end-pitch/ http://beafreelanceblogger.com/guest-post-rejection/ http://beafreelanceblogger.com/numbers-game/ http://beafreelanceblogger.com/jedi-freelance-blogging-fear/ http://beafreelanceblogger.com/relationship-editor/ http://beafreelanceblogger.com/rock-guest-post/ BeAFreelanceBlogger.com Page 5 Back to Contents Page What do the listings mean? 
Here’s an example listing that explains what’s what: Example Blog Name Then an overview of the blog with notes on topics, types of submission they accept, and specific submission methods. 
Blog Homepage: The URL for the site’s front page. 
Contributor Information: The URL for the blog’s guidelines for contributors - read and follow them! 
Pay: The pay rate (or rates) we’ve confirmed either with the publication or with writers who’ve been published there. 
Contributor Byline: “Yes” means your name is published with your post. 
Most blogs give a byline. 
Contributor Bio: That’s a short piece of text about you, usually shown at the end of your post. 
Some blogs include your photo, and let you add a link to your website. 
Other blogs don’t display a bio at all. 
Rights: The publication rights the blog buys from you when they pay you. 
http://beafreelanceblogger.com/ BeAFreelanceBlogger.com Page 6 Back to Contents Page Art, Design and Photography Blogs Cgituts+ Cgituts+ is a blog about computer generated images, 3D graphics and visual effects. 
They accept submissions of written or video-based tutorials for any CGI-related software. 
Pitch your idea to the editor first, then submit a folder of all the supporting media along with the post HTML code written to fit the Cgituts+ template. 
(Note: As Cgituts+ has absorbed the now-defunct Aetuts+, they occasionally accept posts about Adobe After Effects software). 
Blog Homepage: http://cgi.tutsplus.com/ Contributor Information: http://tutsplus.com/teach Pay: From $50 for quick tips to “make an offer” for longer tutorials. 
Contributor Byline: Yes. 
Contributor Bio: Yes, but not shown until you click the author’s byline. 
Includes a few lines with links and a photo. 
Rights: Buying exclusive online publication rights. 
http://beafreelanceblogger.com/ http://cgi.tutsplus.com/ http://tutsplus.com/teach BeAFreelanceBlogger.com Page 7 Back to Contents Page Art, Design and Photography Blogs Photoshop Tutorials This is another popular Photoshop tutorials blog. 
They accept pitches for short tips and longer comprehensive tutorials, in a step-by-step walkthrough format with plenty of images to illustrate the technique. 
They also publish tutorials on photography and Photoshop Elements. 
You must use their Word document template (download it from the contributor information page) for your submission. 
Blog Homepage: http://photoshoptutorials.ws Contributor Information: http://photoshoptutorials.ws/money-photoshop/ Pay: From $50 for short tutorials to $150-$300 for full-length tutorials. 
Contributor Byline: Yes. 
Contributor Bio: Yes, but only shown at the very end of paginated posts. 
A few lines with photo and links. 
Rights: Buying exclusive online publication rights. 
http://beafreelanceblogger.com/ http://photoshoptutorials.ws/ http://photoshoptutorials.ws/money-photoshop/ BeAFreelanceBlogger.com Page 8 Back to Contents Page Art, Design and Photography Blogs Phototuts+ This photography and Photoshop blog accepts submissions in several different formats, including videos, articles, and step-by-step written tutorials. 
Pay rates depend on post length and complexity. 
Pitch your idea first, then submit the post as HTML code using the Phototuts+ template. 
Blog Homepage: http://photography.tutsplus.com/ Contributor Information: http://tutsplus.com/teach Pay: From $50 for quick tips to “make an offer” for longer tutorials (1500+ words). 
Contributor Byline: Yes. 
Contributor Bio: Yes, but not shown until you click the author’s byline. 
Includes a few lines with links and a photo. 
Rights: Buying exclusive online publication rights. 
You can republish your post offline, but not online. 
http://beafreelanceblogger.com/ http://photography.tutsplus.com/ http://tutsplus.com/teach BeAFreelanceBlogger.com Page 9 Back to Contents Page Art, Design and Photography Blogs Psdtuts+ This blog’s all about Adobe 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

