How InputStreamReader.read(char[] cbuf) determine the end of the stream (I/O and Streams forum at Coderanch) Post Reply Bookmark Topic Watch Topic New Topic Campbell Ritchie Jeanne Boyarsky Ron McLeod Paul Clapham Junilu Lacar   Sky Loi Ranch Hand Posts: 65 posted 11 years ago Number of slices to send: Optional 'thank-you' note: Send Hi, all, About method public int read(char[] cbuf) in InputStreamReader, how will it determine the end of stream and return -1? 
By special chars or timeout? 
Thanks   Rob Spoor Sheriff posted 11 years ago Number of slices to send: Optional 'thank-you' note: Send The end of the stream is just that, the end of the stream. 
What that means determines on the source. 
For local files, the end of the stream is reached when all characters (or bytes with an InputStream) have been read. 
For files on a web server or FTP server, the end of the stream is reached when the server says that all characters / bytes have been read. 
For HTTP (web servers) that is mostly determined by the content-length header. 
For sockets, the end of the stream is reached when the other side has closed the connection and everything that has been sent before is read. 
For other sources you'll have to check it out.   
Sky Loi Ranch Hand Posts: 65 posted 11 years ago Number of slices to send: Optional 'thank-you' note: Send   If you two don't stop this rough-housing somebody is going to end up crying. 
Sit down and read this tiny ad: the value of filler advertising in 2021 https://coderanch.com/t/730886/filler-advertising
</TEXT>
</DOC>

